%[text] # Vapor Model: Saturation Vapor Pressure, Density, and Diffusion
%[text] This script documents the three vapor formulations used in icemodel and their derivative chains. It reconciles the Liston/Buck, Jordan/SNTHERM, and Ambaum/Romps approaches to computing the vapor heat diffusion coefficient $k\_v$.
%%
%[text] ## **Formulations covered**
%[text] 1\. **Buck (1981)** — empirical fit: $e\_s = a \\exp\\left\[\\frac{b(T-T\_f)}{c+T-T\_f}\\right\]$
%[text] 2\. **Jordan (1991) / SNTHERM** — constant-$L$ Clausius-Clapeyron: $e\_s = e\_{s\_0} \\exp\\left\[\\frac{L\_s}{R\_v T\_f}\\left(\\frac{T-T\_f}{T}\\right)\\right\]$
%[text] 3\. **Ambaum (2020) / Romps (2021)** — Rankine-Kirchhoff: $e\\\_s = a \\exp\\left\[\\frac{b}{T}\\right\] T^c$
%[text] ### **Key result**
%[text] Liston's $k\_v$ definition omits the $-e\_s/T$ term from the vapor density derivative, giving $k\\\_v = \\frac{D\_e L\_s}{R\_v T} \\frac{de\_s}{dT}$ rather than Jordan's correct $k\_v = D\_e L\_s \\frac{d\\rho\_v}{dT}$. This error is documented in Section 3 below.
%%
%[text] ## 1. Core relationships
%[text] ### Vapor density from vapor pressure
%[text] The ideal gas law relates saturation vapor density to vapor pressure:
%[text] $\\rho\_v = \\frac{e\_s}{R\_v T}$
%[text] ### Vapor density derivative
%[text] By the quotient rule:
%[text] $\\frac{d\\rho\_v}{dT} = \\frac{1}{R\_v T}\\left(\\frac{de\_s}{dT} - \\frac{e\_s}{T}\\right)$
%[text] Or equivalently in terms of $\\rho\_v$:
%[text] $\\frac{d\\rho\_v}{dT} = \\frac{1}{R\_v T}\\frac{de\_s}{dT} - \\frac{\\rho\_v}{T}$
%[text] ### Vapor heat diffusion coefficient
%[text] The effective vapor thermal diffusion coefficient (Jordan, above Eq. 63):
%[text] $k\_v = D\_e L\_s \\frac{d\\rho\_v}{dT}$
%[text] Expressed in terms of vapor pressure:
%[text] $k\_v = \\frac{D\_e L\_s}{R\_v T}\\left(\\frac{de\_s}{dT} - \\frac{e\_s}{T}\\right)$
%[text] ### Vapor diffusivity
%[text] $D\_e = D\_{e0}\\left(\\frac{T}{T\_f}\\right)^n$
%[text] where $n$ is the temperature exponent. Jordan uses $n=6$; Anderson (1976) uses $n=14$.
%%
%[text] ### Gas constant note
%[text] Romps (2021) uses $c\_p - c\_v$ in place of $R\_v$. This follows \[Mayer's relation\](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Julius\_Robert\_von\_Mayer) for an ideal gas:
%[text] $R = C\_p - C\_v$
%[text] For water vapor: $R\_v = c\_{pv} - c\_{vv} = 461$ J kg$^{-1}$ K$^{-1}$.
clean

Tf = 273.16;
Ls = 2.834e6;
Lv = 2.501e6;
Rv = 461.5;
es0 = 611;
T = (250:0.5:274)';
Tdep = T - Tf;
%%
%[text] ## 2. Three saturation vapor pressure formulations
%[text] ### 2a. Buck (1981) — empirical formula
%[text] $e\_s = A \\exp\\left\[\\frac{B(T-T\_f)}{C + T - T\_f}\\right\]$
%[text] $\\frac{de\_s}{dT} = e\_s \\frac{BC}{(C + T\_d)^2}$
%[text] Buck coefficients over ice:
A_buck = 611.15;
B_buck = 22.452;
C_buck = 272.55;

es_buck = A_buck * exp(B_buck * Tdep ./ (C_buck + Tdep));
des_dT_buck = es_buck .* B_buck .* C_buck ./ (C_buck + Tdep).^2;
%%
%[text] ### 2b. Jordan (1991) / SNTHERM — constant-$L$ Clausius-Clapeyron
%[text] $e\_s = e\_{s0} \\exp\\left\[\\frac{L\_s}{R\_v T\_f}\\left(\\frac{T-T\_f}{T}\\right)\\right\]$
%[text] This separates into two exponentials:
%[text] $e\_s = e\_{s0} \\exp\\left\[\\frac{L\_s}{R\_v T\_f}\\right\] \\exp\\left\[-\\frac{L\_s}{R\_v T}\\right\]$
%[text] The derivative is:
%[text] $\\frac{de\_s}{dT} = e\_s \\frac{L\_s}{R\_v T^2}$
es_jordan = es0 * exp(Ls / (Rv * Tf) * Tdep ./ T);
des_dT_jordan = es_jordan .* Ls ./ (Rv * T.^2);
%%
%[text] Jordan's combined constants for SNTHERM grain growth (Eq. 20):
%[text] $\\frac{d\\rho\_v}{dT} = \\frac{c\_{1k}}{T^2}\\left(\\frac{L\_k}{R\_v T} - 1\\right)\\exp\\left(-\\frac{L\_k}{R\_v T}\\right)$
%[text] where $c\_{1,ice} = 8.047 \\times 10^9$ and $c\_{1,liq} = 5.726 \\times 10^8$ \[kg m$^{-3}$ K\].
c1_ice = 8.047e9;
c1_liq = 5.726e8;
Ti_exp = Ls ./ (Rv * T);
drov_dT_jordan = c1_ice ./ T.^2 .* (Ti_exp - 1) .* exp(-Ti_exp);
%%
%[text] ### 2c. Ambaum (2020) / Romps (2021) — Rankine-Kirchhoff
%[text] $e\_s = a \\exp\\left(\\frac{b}{T}\\right) T^c$
%[text] $\\frac{de\_s}{dT} = \\frac{e\_s}{T}\\left(c - \\frac{b}{T}\\right)$
%[text] $\\frac{d^2 e\_s}{dT^2} = \\frac{e\_s}{T^2}\\left\[(c-1)\\left(c - \\frac{2b}{T}\\right) + \\frac{b^2}{T^2}\\right\]$
%[text] Vapor density derivative:
%[text] $\\frac{d\\rho\_v}{dT} = \\frac{\\rho\_v}{T}\\left(c - \\frac{b}{T} - 1\\right)$
%[text] This is the production formulation in icemodel. Coefficients are derived in VAPORINIT from physical constants following Ambaum (2020).
[es_amb, des_dT_amb, d2es_dT2_amb, rov_amb, drov_dT_amb] = VAPPRESS2(T, false);
%[text] ### Compare formulations
figure('Name', 'Saturation Vapor Pressure: Three Formulations') %[output:5fa07397]
tiledlayout(1, 2, 'TileSpacing', 'compact', 'Padding', 'compact') %[output:5fa07397]

nexttile; hold on %[output:5fa07397]
plot(T, es_buck, 'b-') %[output:5fa07397]
plot(T, es_jordan, 'g--') %[output:5fa07397]
plot(T, es_amb, 'r:') %[output:5fa07397]
set(gca, 'YScale', 'log') %[output:5fa07397]
ylabel('e_s [Pa]'); xlabel('T [K]') %[output:5fa07397]
legend('Buck', 'Jordan', 'Ambaum', 'Location', 'northwest') %[output:5fa07397]
title('Saturation vapor pressure') %[output:5fa07397]

nexttile; hold on %[output:5fa07397]
plot(T, des_dT_buck, 'b-') %[output:5fa07397]
plot(T, des_dT_jordan, 'g--') %[output:5fa07397]
plot(T, des_dT_amb, 'r:') %[output:5fa07397]
set(gca, 'YScale', 'log') %[output:5fa07397]
ylabel('de_s/dT [Pa K^{-1}]'); xlabel('T [K]') %[output:5fa07397]
legend('Buck', 'Jordan', 'Ambaum', 'Location', 'northwest') %[output:5fa07397]
title('First derivative') %[output:5fa07397]
%%
%[text] ## 3. Reconciling Liston and Jordan: the $k\_v$ error
%[text] Two definitions of $k\_v$ appear in the literature:
%[text] **Liston (Eq. 3):** $k\_v = \\frac{D\_e L\_s}{R\_v T}\\frac{de\_s}{dT}$
%[text] **Jordan (above Eq. 63):** $k\_v = D\_e L\_s \\frac{d\\rho\_v}{dT}$
%[text] Jordan's definition is correct — it follows from $\\rho\_v = e\_s / (R\_v T)$, so:
%[text] $\\frac{d\\rho\_v}{dT} = \\frac{1}{R\_v T}\\left(\\frac{de\_s}{dT} - \\frac{e\_s}{T}\\right)$
%[text] Plugging into Jordan's $k\_v$:
%[text] $k\_v = \\frac{D\_e L\_s}{R\_v T}\\left(\\frac{de\_s}{dT} - \\frac{e\_s}{T}\\right)$
%[text] **Liston's formula is missing the \\$-e\_s/T\\$ term.** In Buck notation:
%[text] Liston: $k\_v = D\_e L\_s \\rho\_v \\frac{bc}{(c+T\_d)^2}$
%[text] Jordan: $k\_v = D\_e L\_s \\rho\_v \\left(\\frac{bc}{(c+T\_d)^2} - \\frac{1}{T}\\right)$
%[text] The incorrect reconciliation step (documented for reference):
%%
%[text] Starting from Jordan's correct vapor density derivative:
rov_buck = es_buck ./ (Rv * T);
drov_dT_buck = rov_buck .* (B_buck * C_buck ./ (C_buck + Tdep).^2 - 1 ./ T);

nd = 6;
De0 = 9e-5;
De = De0 * (T / Tf) .^ nd;
%[text]  Correct (Jordan): $k\_v = D\_e L\_s \\frac{d\\rho\_v}{dT}$
k_vap_jordan = Ls * De .* drov_dT_buck;
%[text] Incorrect (Liston): $k\_v = \\frac{D\_e L\_s}{R\_v T}\\frac{de\_s}{dT}$ (missing $-e\_s/T$)
k_vap_liston = Ls * De ./ (Rv * T) .* des_dT_buck;
%%
%[text] The original error was attempting to reconcile the two by substituting $\\rho\_v bc/(c+T\_d)^2 = d\\rho\_v/dT + \\rho\_v/T$ into the Liston expression:
k_vap_wrong = Ls * De .* (drov_dT_buck + rov_buck ./ T);
%[text] This gives Liston's answer, not Jordan's. The error is that Liston's formula was used as the starting point.
%%
%[text] Verify: Liston's formula equals the incorrect reconciliation
assert(max(abs(k_vap_wrong - k_vap_liston)) < 1e-10, ...
   'Incorrect reconciliation should match Liston')
%%
%[text] Compare correct vs incorrect $k\_v$:
figure('Name', 'k_v: Liston vs Jordan') %[output:14016836]
tiledlayout(1, 2, 'TileSpacing', 'compact', 'Padding', 'compact') %[output:14016836]

nexttile; hold on %[output:14016836]
plot(T, k_vap_jordan, 'b-') %[output:14016836]
plot(T, k_vap_liston, 'r--') %[output:14016836]
ylabel('k_v [W m^{-1} K^{-1}]'); xlabel('T [K]') %[output:14016836]
legend('Jordan (correct)', 'Liston (missing -e_s/T)', 'Location', 'northwest') %[output:14016836]
title('Vapor heat diffusion coefficient') %[output:14016836]

nexttile %[output:14016836]
plot(T, (k_vap_liston - k_vap_jordan) ./ k_vap_jordan * 100) %[output:14016836]
ylabel('Relative error [%]'); xlabel('T [K]') %[output:14016836]
title('Liston overestimate') %[output:14016836]
%%
%[text] ## 4. SNTHERM implementation
%[text] Jordan (1991) Eq. 20 expresses the vapor density derivative using pre-computed constants:
%[text] $\\frac{d\\rho\_v}{dT} = \\frac{c\_{1k}}{T^2}\\left(\\frac{L\_k}{R\_v T} - 1\\right)\\exp\\left(-\\frac{L\_k}{R\_v T}\\right)$
%[text] This is a self-consistent system with the constant-$L$ Clausius-Clapeyron $e\_s$ formula. In icemodel, this is used only in GRAINSIZE and should not be mixed with Ambaum coefficients.
%[text] The leading coefficient $c\_{1k}$ absorbs the reference vapor pressure and latent heat:
%[text] $c\_{1k} = \\frac{e\_{s0} L\_k}{R\_v^2} \\exp\\left\[\\frac{L\_k}{R\_v T\_f}\\right\]$
%[text] For ice: $c\_{1,ice} = 8.047 \\times 10^9$ kg m$^{-3}$ K
%[text] For liquid: $c\_{1,liq} = 5.726 \\times 10^8$ kg m$^{-3}$ K
k_vap_sntherm = Ls * De .* drov_dT_jordan;
%%
%[text] ## 5. Ambaum / Romps derivative chain
%[text] The Ambaum (2020) / Romps (2021) Rankine-Kirchhoff formulation:
%[text] $e\_s = a \\exp\\left(\\frac{b}{T}\\right) T^c$
%[text] All derivatives follow from the product rule on $\\exp(b/T) \\cdot T^c$:
%[text] $\\frac{de\_s}{dT} = \\frac{e\_s}{T}\\left(c - \\frac{b}{T}\\right)$
%[text] $\\frac{d\\rho\_v}{dT} = \\frac{\\rho\_v}{T}\\left(c - \\frac{b}{T} - 1\\right)$
%[text] $k\_v = D\_e L\_s \\frac{d\\rho\_v}{dT} = \\frac{D\_e L\_s}{R\_v T}\\left(\\frac{de\_s}{dT} - \\frac{e\_s}{T}\\right)$
%[text] The second derivatives (for Newton solvers):
%[text] $\\frac{d^2 e\_s}{dT^2} = \\frac{e\_s}{T^2}\\left\[\\left(c-1\\right)\\left(c - \\frac{2b}{T}\\right) + \\frac{b^2}{T^2}\\right\]$
%[text] $\\frac{d^2 \\rho\_v}{dT^2} = \\frac{\\rho\_v}{T^2}\\left\[(c-2)\\left(c-1-\\frac{2b}{T}\\right) + \\frac{b^2}{T^2}\\right\]$
%[text] Note: the Ambaum derivatives are simpler than Buck's for higher orders. Buck's $d^2 e\_s/dT^2$ involves $(c+T\_d)^3$ denominators, while Ambaum's involves only powers of $T$.
%%
%[text] ### Symbolic verification of derivatives
%[text] The symbolic derivatives confirm the analytical expressions.
syms T_sym a_sym b_sym c_sym R_v_sym

es_sym = a_sym * exp(b_sym / T_sym) * T_sym ^ c_sym;
des_sym = diff(es_sym, T_sym);
d2es_sym = diff(es_sym, T_sym, 2);

rov_sym = es_sym / (R_v_sym * T_sym);
drov_sym = diff(rov_sym, T_sym);
d2rov_sym = diff(rov_sym, T_sym, 2);
%%
%[text] Substitute $e\_s$ back in to verify the closed forms:
syms e_s_sub rho_v_sub

des_closed = subs(des_sym, es_sym, e_s_sub);
des_closed = subs(des_closed, T_sym^(c_sym - 1) * a_sym * exp(b_sym / T_sym), e_s_sub / T_sym) %[output:726993a7]

drov_closed = subs(drov_sym, rov_sym, rho_v_sub);
drov_closed = subs(drov_closed, T_sym^(c_sym - 1) * a_sym * exp(b_sym / T_sym) / (R_v_sym * T_sym), rho_v_sub / T_sym) %[output:164bf608]
%%
%[text] ## 6. Compact $k\_v$ form
%[text] Following the Jordan derivation for the constant-$L$ case, one can write $k\_v$ in a compact form using the $\\alpha-\\beta$ notation:
%[text] $\\alpha = \\frac{D\_{e0} L\_s e\_{s0} \\exp\\left\[\\frac{L\_s}{R\_v T\_f}\\right\]}{T\_f^n R\_v}$
%[text] $\\beta = \\frac{L\_s}{R\_v}$
%[text] Then: $k\_v = \\alpha T^{n-2}\\left(\\frac{\\beta}{T} - 1\\right)\\exp\\left(-\\frac{\\beta}{T}\\right)$
beta = Ls / Rv;
alpha = De0 * Ls * es0 * exp(Ls / (Rv * Tf)) / (Tf ^ nd * Rv);
k_v_compact = alpha * T .^ (nd - 2) .* (beta ./ T - 1) .* exp(-beta ./ T);

figure('Name', 'k_v compact form') %[output:83d4516c]
plot(T, k_v_compact) %[output:83d4516c]
xlabel('T [K]'); ylabel('k_v [W m^{-1} K^{-1}]') %[output:83d4516c]
title('Vapor heat transfer coefficient (Jordan compact form)') %[output:83d4516c]
%%
%[text] ## 7. Diffusivity and Yen's enhancement
%[text] The vapor diffusivity is:
%[text] $D\_e = D\_{e0}\\left(\\frac{T}{T\_f}\\right)^n$
%[text] Jordan uses $D\_{e0} = 9.2 \\times 10^{-5}$ m$^2$ s$^{-1}$, $n = 6$.
%[text] Anderson (1976) uses $D\_{e0} = 9.0 \\times 10^{-5}$ m$^2$ s$^{-1}$, $n = 14$.
%[text] The difference has negligible impact on the solution because $k\_v$ is a small contributor to the effective thermal conductivity $k\_e$ except in rare cases (very low ice and liquid content in winter).
%[text] ### Yen's diffusivity enhancement
%[text] Yen et al. (1981) proposed enhancing the diffusivity for unconsolidated near-surface snow to account for ventilation. This can be applied as a multiplicative factor:
%[text] $D\_e' = D\_{ep} \\cdot D\_e$
%[text] where $D\_{ep} \\approx 10$ (Yen's enhancement factor).
%[text] Alternatively, a density-dependent form from Sturm and Benson (1997):
%[text] $D\_e' = D\_e + 0.0513 \\cdot \\rho\_s^{3.2} \\cdot G^{0.615}$
%[text] where $\\rho\_s$ is snow density in g cm$^{-3}$ and $G$ is the temperature gradient magnitude \[K m$^{-1}$\].
%[text] These enhancements are not currently active in production code.
%%
%[text] ## 8. Buck derivative definitions
%[text] For reference, the Buck derivatives use the substitution $\\sigma\_1$:
%[text] $\\sigma\_1 = \\frac{bc}{(c^\* + T)^2} = \\frac{1}{e\_s}\\frac{de\_s}{dT} = \\frac{1}{\\rho\_v}\\frac{d\\rho\_v}{dT} + \\frac{1}{T}$
%[text] And $\\sigma\_2 = \\frac{2bc}{(c^\* + T)^3} = \\sigma\_1 \\cdot \\frac{2}{c^\* + T}$
%[text] where $c^\* = c - T\_f$ (the Celsius-offset form).
%[text] The second derivative of vapor density:
%[text] $\\frac{d^2\\rho\_v}{dT^2} = \\frac{\\rho\_v}{T}\\left(\\frac{1}{T} - \\frac{2}{c^\* + T}\\right) + \\frac{d\\rho\_v}{dT}\\left(\\frac{1}{\\rho\_v}\\frac{d\\rho\_v}{dT} - \\frac{2}{c^\* + T}\\right)$
%[text] Note: the second derivative expressed in terms of $e\_s$ (minimum operations, implemented in VAPPRESS):
%[text] $\\frac{d^2\\rho\_v}{dT^2} = \\frac{1}{R\_v T}\\left\[\\frac{de\_s}{dT}\\left(\\frac{1}{e\_s}\\frac{de\_s}{dT} - \\frac{2}{c^\*}\\right) - \\frac{2}{T}\\left(\\frac{de\_s}{dT} - \\frac{e\_s}{T}\\right)\\right\]$
%%
%[text] ## References
%[text] - Ambaum, M. H. P. (2020). Accurate, simple equation for saturated vapour pressure over water and ice. \*QJRMS\*, 146, 4252-4258. DOI: 10.1002/qj.3899
%[text] - Anderson, E. A. (1976). A point energy and mass balance model of a snow cover. \*NOAA Tech. Rep. NWS 19\*.
%[text] - Buck, A. L. (1981). New equations for computing vapor pressure and enhancement factor. \*J. Appl. Meteorol.\*, 20(12), 1527-1532.
%[text] - Jordan, R. (1991). A one-dimensional temperature model for a snow cover. \*CRREL Special Rep. 91-16\*.
%[text] - Liston, G. E., et al. (1999). A meteorological distribution system for high-resolution terrestrial modeling. \*J. Hydrometeorol.\*, 1, 71-82.
%[text] - Romps, D. M. (2021). The Rankine-Kirchhoff approximations for moist thermodynamics. \*QJRMS\*, 147(741), 3493-3497. DOI: 10.1002/qj.4154
%[text] - Sturm, M. and Benson, C. S. (1997). Vapor transport, grain growth and depth-hoar development in the subarctic snow. \*J. Glaciol.\*, 43(143), 42-59.
%[text] - Yen, Y. C., et al. (1981). \*CRREL Rep. 81-1\*. \

